title: For Sale/Trade:  Diamondback DB9 – “YJ” Series - Black - 9mm
postcontent: Almost NIB Diamondback DB9 (9mm) in black. You can see from the photos this gun is in excellent shape. The serial number begins with “YJ” which is the most recent series Diamondback makes.  They finally got it right with this series of the gun and this one has performed flawlessly.  I'm the original owner.I bought it new a few weeks ago and it has approximately 50 rounds through it. It really didn’t need any breaking in and has worked just fine from the start.I truly wanted this gun to work for me but it’s a little snappy for my old arthritic hands. That’s a shame because this one’s very reliable, unlike some of the older series DB9’s out there.The DB9 is an outstanding pocket-carry design with a smooth trigger, very similar to a Glock (even down to its take-down method). It's light weight with an ultra-flat profile (11 oz. weight & 0.8 inch width) and that makes it the lightest, slimmest, and smallest 9mm available.  Even though it's the same size as a Ruger LCP, you won’t have to settle for a .380. It's easy to pocket carry and just disappears in your pocket or purse.I’ve found that the DB9 likes a steady diet of Remington UMC 115 gr JHP’s. These rounds run toward the lower end of the SAAMI spec for overall length. I’ve put a digital caliper on these rounds and they average about a thousandth of an inch shorter than most other 9mm rounds…certainly within the SAAMI spec but just short enough to accommodate the tight tolerances of this micro-nine. This DB9 loves them and if you feed it well, it will perform for you.The full package comes with the original Diamondback box, soft case, trigger lock, all paperwork that came from the factory (as shown in photo). It also includes two 6-round mags supplied by Diamondback, with a pinkie extension on one of them and a +2 mag extension on the other.  Both mags are the good ones made in Italy. The gun includes the lifetime factory warranty.  The gun also has a Talon grip installed (easily removed if you don't like them) and a nice leather pocket-carry sleeve for the extra mag.I prefer face-to-face transfer in east Texas without shipping. Must be a legal buyer, 21 or over with valid TX driver’s license or permit.  I’m in College Station so the triangle formed by Austin, DFW, and Houston is do-able.  Let's meet halfway or even partway to reduce our driving time.  That would be much appreciated.If I don’t respond to your email immediately, it only means I’m at work and I’ll respond soon after I get home. If the ad is still up, the gun is still available.The price is firm.  My only trade interest would be a Glock-42 (with cash added on my end).  Low-ball offers will be respectfully ignored. Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Tanfoglio GT 32 XEB
postcontent: Little double-stack .32 ACP. Resembles a Beretta with the open top slide. All steel with wood grips.Holds 12 + 1, comes with 2 magazines. Made in Italy by Armi Tanfoglio Giuseppe, imported by Excam. Tanfoglio still makes guns as most people know, but this model was discontinued in either the 1980s or 90s. You can still find plenty of parts for it on Numrich or elsewhere online, though.Hammer fired, single action. Has a firing pin safety, half cock, and a magazine disconnect safety (which I’m sure you could take out if you so wanted). Has a takedown switch that’s a little interesting. Just like the takedown lever on a lot of handguns (like the Bersa Thunder), but it functions as a switch instead of being spring loaded, so you don’t have to hold it down to pull the slide off. It also disconnects the trigger when you activate it, so they’ve labeled it as a secondary safety. Has good sights, overall condition looks very good with some slight wear on the wood grips and a small scratch near the chamber.This gun does need a little bit of gunsmithing attention, however. The disassembly switch works as a safety, but the firing pin safety does not work. Might need a new safety switch for it.UPDATE: I currently have this firearm at a gunsmith in order to fix the issue with the primary safety. When I get it back, I will remove this line of text.

This type of action allows the barrel to remain solidly fixed to the frame, resulting in improved accuracy over pistols with pivoting barrels (like the U.S. M1911 series). The low bore axis of the vz. 82 provides for less muzzle rise and quicker follow-up shots. For added convenience, both the frame-mounted thumb safety and the magazine release are ambidextrous.

title: For Sale:  USED - CZECH CZ 24 VERY EARLY BRITISH PROOFED PISTOL WITH HOLSTER (ICN8179)
postcontent: This is one of the very first CZ 24 pistols ever made…and it is Czech proofed and British proofed! CZ Model 1924 (vz. 24), in .380 ACP, was the standard Czechoslovak Army pistol of the inter-war period manufactured by Česka Zbrojovka (CZ) in Prague (as displayed on a rib on the top of the slide “Česka Zbrojovka A.S. v Praze”). There is something special and intriguing about this pistol. Extremely low Serial Number: 1259. No import marks. All components match: barrel, frame, and slide. The pistol has 98% of its original bright blue finish remaining. The trigger, hammer, and extractor retain about 98% of the original straw color. It is fitted with one-piece, smooth and well-preserved walnut grips. Excellent overall condition. Overall, approximately 200,000 CZ 24 pistols were made. According to most sources, the regular serial number range for the CZ 24 pistol is: 12,000-190,000 (according to the book “Know Your Czechoslovakian Pistols” by R. J. Berger, there were some pistols produced as part of small international orders/contracts in a separate serial number range, for example, all 9-shot CZ 24 pistols range from serial number 1 to about 3,100, and are dated from 1929 to 1931). The serial number of this pistol is 1259! However, it is not a 9-shot pistol. The three nearest lowest serial numbers we have seen in years were in the 10,000, 11,000, and 12,000 range…and nothing in between. Again, our pistol’s serial number is 1,259. Based on the proof marks, the featured pistol seems to be a part of the original order for 20,000 CZ 24 pistols completed in June 1926. The pistol is factory dated 25 (1925) and it stayed in the factory warehouse until purchased by the Military in 1926. It displays the 1926 acceptance “J, rampant lion, 26” mark of Czechoslovak Military. The pistol is unit marked to the Czechoslovak Army’s 17th infantry regiment (17P 39). If this pistol wasn’t a part of a small international contract, it had to be captured by the British Army during WWII. In June 1945, the British Army stood at 3 million men, and with its Allies, it was victorious against Nazi Germany in Tunisia, Italy (1943), France and Germany (1944-45) etc. But then how did the featured CZ 24 end up in the United States? The British have laws, dating back to 1813, relating to the sale of guns that go some way to protecting the public from unsafe guns of any age. All British guns are tested before they can be sold by a system known as “proofing”. This takes place in one of the UK proof houses: Birmingham or London. Pistols that received British proofs prior to being disposed of in the 1950s, should have matching proofs on the slide, receiver (frame), and barrel. Britain has used two commonly found sets of proof marks. One is from the Proof act of 1925-1955, the other is the Proof act of 1955. The 1955 proof act removed the requirement to mark the pistol “Not English Make”. Our featured CZ 24 pistol displays the “Not English Make” mark underneath the 1926 acceptance “J, rampant lion, 26” mark of Czechoslovak Military. Therefore, the pistol was brought to Britain before 1955. Our pistol displays the Birmingham Proof House marks: crown over “BP” on barrel, crown over “NP” on barrel, and a crown over "BV" on barrel, slide, and receiver (frame). These Birmingham Proof House marks date back to 1925-1954. The circle around the marks means “Not English Made”. “BP” surmounted by a crown represents “Provisional and Definitive Proof”. “BV” surmounted by a crown is a “View Mark”. “NP” surmounted by a crown is a “Definitive Nitro Proof”. The CZ 24 was an improved version of the CZ 22, which had been licensed from Mauser. Production of the CZ 24 started in August 1925. The original order for 20,000 pistols was completed in June 1926. More orders followed, and by the end of 1929, 100,000 pistols had been accepted by the Military and Gendarmerie, called in Czechoslovakia the “Četnictvo”. An inventory on January 1, 1939, showed the Czechoslovak Army and Air Force had on hand 171,756 CZ 24 pistols. CZ 24 is a meticulously crafted, well-built, robust, and reliable pistol that was very highly thought of at the time. During the German occupation (March 1939 – May 1945), the Czechoslovak Armed Forces were disarmed, and all the weapons were utilized by Germany and its allies. The CZ 24 pistols were not marked by the Germans, in any way, except for those used by the German Navy. CZ 24 pistols were also issued to the German Air Force, and Waffen-SS. The pistol is fitted with one-piece, smooth wood grips. Magazine capacity is eight rounds, and a Mauser Model 1910-style safety switch is mounted to the left of the pistol. The pistol is housed in an original leather flap holster containing one extra CZ 24 magazine.

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1886 38-56
location: new jersey, New Jersey, United States
postcontent: Winchester 1886 rifle chambered in .38-56 with a 23 ½” full octagon barrel and Beech folding globe front sight.Denotes a manufacture date of 1891. The barrel has been shortened and all metal has been refinished. The wood may or may not have the original finish but has no splits or cracks. There are some small dings and scratches and chips and someone has carved a small “W” on the left side near the receiver. The bore has some light pitting but is bright and has plenty of rifling remaining to make a good shooting rifle. The action is tight and really feels good when you work the lever with no play or sloppiness. To sum up here you are looking at a good tight Winchester model 1886 with a decent bore that should make a good shooting rifle.
